# Kubernetes Deployment Playbook

## Prerequisites

- [x] `kubectl` CLI installed and configured
- [x] Cluster access verified
- [ ] Review deployment manifests
- [ ] Verify image tags match release version

## Pre-Deployment Checks

```bash
# Verify cluster connectivity
kubectl cluster-info

# Check current deployment status
kubectl get deployments -n production

# Review pending changes
kubectl diff -f manifests/
```

W> Always run `kubectl diff` before applying changes to production.

## Deployment Steps

### 1. Update ConfigMaps

```bash
kubectl apply -f manifests/configmap.yaml -n production
```

### 2. Deploy New Version

```bash
kubectl apply -f manifests/deployment.yaml -n production
```

### 3. Monitor Rollout

```bash
kubectl rollout status deployment/api-server -n production --timeout=300s
```

## Rollback Procedure

!> If the deployment shows errors, roll back immediately.

```bash
# Check rollout history
kubectl rollout history deployment/api-server -n production

# Rollback to previous version
kubectl rollout undo deployment/api-server -n production
```

## Health Check Endpoints

| Service | Endpoint | Expected |
| --- | --- | :---: |
| API Server | `/health` | 200 OK |
| Worker | `/health` | 200 OK |
| Scheduler | `/health` | 200 OK |
| Gateway | `/status` | 200 OK |

## Post-Deployment

- [ ] Verify all pods are running
- [ ] Check application logs for errors
- [ ] Run smoke tests
- [ ] Update deployment tracker
- [ ] Notify team in Slack

N> Allow 10 minutes of monitoring after deployment before declaring success.

T> Use `kubectl logs -f` to tail logs in real time during the deployment window.

X> If more than 20% of pods fail readiness checks, trigger an automatic rollback.
